description: From Middle English replete (adjective) and repleten (verb), from Old French replet, from Latin repletus.

adjectives.description: replete (comparative more replete, superlative most replete)

entries.meaning: Gorged, filled to near the point of bursting, especially with food or drink.

verbs.description: replete (third-person singular simple present repletes, present participle repleting, simple past and past participle repleted)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To fill to repletion, or restore something that has been depleted.
